373
00:35:16,843 --> 00:35:21,507
I've been stung so many times,
I have immunity.

374
00:35:21,614 --> 00:35:23,809
They barely even hurt me.

375
00:35:23,917 --> 00:35:27,683
But since you don't, you need
to know beeyard etiquette.

376
00:35:27,787 --> 00:35:31,018
- Beeyard etiquette?
- You see...

377
00:35:31,124 --> 00:35:33,115
the world's really
just one big beeyard.

378
00:35:33,226 --> 00:35:35,990
The same rules work in both places.

379
00:35:37,430 --> 00:35:41,992
Don't be afraid, as no life-lovin' bee
wants to sting you.

380
00:35:42,101 --> 00:35:47,129
But don't be an idiot.
That's why we wear long sleeves and long pants.

381
00:35:47,240 --> 00:35:51,836
And don't swat.
Don't even think about swattin'.

382
00:35:51,945 --> 00:35:54,709
And above all, send the bees love.

383
00:35:54,814 --> 00:35:58,648
Every little thing wants to be loved.

384
00:36:01,087 --> 00:36:03,078
Let's go.

385
00:36:26,779 --> 00:36:30,306
Now, we'll constantly
be checking the hives.

386
00:36:30,416 --> 00:36:35,251
We have to make sure the queens have enough
room to lay their eggs, otherwise we get swarms.

387
00:36:36,956 --> 00:36:38,685
What do you mean, a swarm?

388
00:36:38,791 --> 00:36:43,023
When you get a queen and a group
of independent-minded bees...

389
00:36:43,129 --> 00:36:49,090
that split off and look for another place to live,
then you get swarms.

390
00:36:49,202 --> 00:36:51,170
And I lose my bees.

391
00:36:51,271 --> 00:36:54,536
So, what we have to do is...

392
00:36:56,009 --> 00:36:57,601
take out the frames
filled with honey...

393
00:36:59,245 --> 00:37:01,042
and put in empty ones.

394
00:37:09,255 --> 00:37:13,214
Now, the smoke, it calms the bees...

395
00:37:13,326 --> 00:37:17,126
and it masks the alarm scent
released by the guard bees.

396
00:37:37,083 --> 00:37:39,745
Why, you ain't scared a lick, huh?

397
00:37:39,852 --> 00:37:43,811
I love you. I love you. I love you.
I love you. I love you.

398
00:37:43,923 --> 00:37:45,914
All right.

399
00:37:55,401 --> 00:37:57,301
Easy movement.

400
00:38:03,376 --> 00:38:04,934
See right there, Lily?

401
00:38:05,044 --> 00:38:09,140
That's the queen... the large one.

402
00:38:14,520 --> 00:38:16,784
<i>That wall behind the house...</i>

403
00:38:16,889 --> 00:38:19,483
Why does it have little pieces
of paper in it?

404
00:38:19,592 --> 00:38:22,254
Oh, well, that's May's wall.

405
00:38:22,362 --> 00:38:24,830
She made it herself.

406
00:38:24,931 --> 00:38:27,491
I guess you noticed
she a little different, huh?

407
00:38:27,600 --> 00:38:29,500
She sure gets upset easy.

408
00:38:32,205 --> 00:38:34,400
She had a twin sister, April.

409
00:38:34,507 --> 00:38:36,941
- The one who died.
- Mm-hmm.

410
00:38:37,043 --> 00:38:41,139
It's like the two of them were
one soul sharing two bodies.

411
00:38:41,247 --> 00:38:44,580
If April got a toothache,
May's gum would plump up red.

412
00:38:44,684 --> 00:38:47,676
One time my father used
a belt strap on April.

413
00:38:47,787 --> 00:38:51,188
I swear, welts rose up
on May's legs too.

414
00:38:53,693 --> 00:38:57,720
When April died, it was like the whole world
became May's twin sister.

415
00:38:57,830 --> 00:39:00,094
And we tried for years
to get her help...

416
00:39:00,199 --> 00:39:03,760
but the doctors just kept
telling us to put her away.

417
00:39:03,870 --> 00:39:07,397
So June and I come up with
this idea of the "wailing wall."

418
00:39:07,507 --> 00:39:12,001
- What kind of wall?
